subject: Manager: add ManagerDiagnosticData handler
commitMessage:
Manager: add ManagerDiagnosticData handler

This change adds a link in the Manager for ALL BMCs to an empty
ManagerDiagnosticData resource and a minimum ManagerDiagnosticData
handler.

Tested to make sure no new errors are introduced with the introduction
of ManagerDiagnosticData.

Signed-off-by: Sui Chen <suichen@google.com>
Change-Id: Iba242bc3b6ebec851dbd26e149d5c92c19a7992e

You seem to have ignored my comment.  You use a number of resources below that you don't include headers for.   Please include what you use.

It seems bmcweb will still build even if I don't include any headers and remove all other handles from redfish.hpp, so I added the headers based on what appears in this file.

List of symbols used and include files:

- crow::App comes from <app.hpp>
- BMCWEB_ROUTE comes from <app.hpp>
- RuleParameterTraits::privileges comes from <routing.hpp> which is included by <app.hpp>
- RuleParameterTraits::methods is same as above
- boost::beast::http::verb::get comes from <boost/beast/http/verb.hpp>, which is included by <privileges.hpp>, which is included by <app.hpp>
- crow::Request comes from <http_request.hpp> which is included by <app.hpp>
- bmcweb::AsyncResp comes from <async_resp.hpp> which is included by <app.hpp>
- jsonValue comes from <nlohmann/json.hpp> which is included by <http_request.hpp> which is in turn included by <app.hpp>
- And finally a std::string

So overall it seems I only need <app.hpp> and <string> for this header file to be self-sufficient, due to the indirect includes that fan out from <app.hpp>.

> It seems bmcweb will still build even if I don't include any headers and remove all other handles from redfish.hpp,

Whether or not it builds today is not the point.  When you don't include the headers you use, it leads to hard-to-debug issues later if the import order changes or the modules you rely on no longer include things you require.

> so I added the headers based on what appears in this file.
> 
> List of symbols used and include files:
> 
> - crow::App comes from <app.hpp>
> - BMCWEB_ROUTE comes from <app.hpp>
> - RuleParameterTraits::privileges comes from <routing.hpp> which is included by <app.hpp>

There is no usages of RuleParameterTraits in this file.  redfish::privileges is provided by privileges.hpp, which you neglect to include here.

> - RuleParameterTraits::methods is same as above
> - boost::beast::http::verb::get comes from <boost/beast/http/verb.hpp>, which is included by <privileges.hpp>, which is included by <app.hpp>

While technically incorrect, this is something we let slide, because it's part of the BMCWEB_ROUTE API, so including app.hpp is guaranteed to get you this define, and any change to internal logic would be a breaking API change, which we'd have to fix anyway.

> - crow::Request comes from <http_request.hpp> which is included by <app.hpp>

You should be explicitly including http_request.hpp.  This is what is meant by "include what you use"

> - bmcweb::AsyncResp comes from <async_resp.hpp> which is included by <app.hpp>

same, you should be including async_resp.hpp.

> - jsonValue comes from <nlohmann/json.hpp> which is included by <http_request.hpp> which is in turn included by <app.hpp>

Which you also should be including.

> - And finally a std::string
> 
> So overall it seems I only need <app.hpp> and <string> for this header file to be self-sufficient, due to the indirect includes that fan out from <app.hpp>.

The whole point of this rule is that when you transiently #include things through other files, it puts a secondary dependency.  Lets say at some point in the future we refactored app.hpp to not directly rely on nlohmann::json (which would happen if we ever got a vitualized httpRequest object).  Now every file that has neglected to #include things would have to be updated.  This has concretely hit us in the past when trying to refactor, which is why we ask for this rule.

Documentation from the google style guide.  See the part that starts with "do not rely on transitive inclusions"

https://google.github.io/styleguide/cppguide.html#Include_What_You_Use

Fixed the reliance on transitive includes.

Also, when you do, please migrate this to a separate method, and using std::bind_front.  There are several examples of this already;  We do this to ensure that our error messages are useful in the event of crashes, and lambdas produce very difficult to read code, and mediocre error messages.

2 things here:

1. Generally Id and Name fields are different.  Id in this case would be ManagerDiagnosticData, given that the uri for this is /bmc/ManagerDiagnosticData

2. Generally the name field is human readable, so something like "Manager Diagnostic Data"

Also, as a matter of consistency, we should probably avoid quotes in names like this, incase a client doesn't escape properly
